<CaseStudyLayout title="Unit-Rate Governance & Contracting Strategy for a $233M Contractor Programme">
  <h1>Unit-Rate Governance & Contracting Strategy for a $233M Contractor Programme</h1>

  <div class="cs-spec">
    <div><p class="k">Functional Topic</p><p class="v">Procurement Governance, Contract Strategy & Commercial Rate Benchmarking</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Industry</p><p class="v">Energy & Utilities</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Support Needed</p><p class="v">Independent Commercial Assessment & Contracting Strategy (pre-RFP)</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Duration</p><p class="v">10 Weeks</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Challenge</h2>
  <p>A major U.S. electric utility was approaching a 2026 renewal of its overhead-construction contracts. Its unit-rate book — the rate catalogue governing how contractors bill — had not been refreshed in five years, unit billing ran well below industry norms, and there was no competitive-tension mechanism, leaving an unquantified above-market exposure heading into the RFP. Leadership needed to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Quantify how much contractor billing was above market — and whether the cause was supplier choice or structural governance.</li>
    <li>Pinpoint where governance failed across 482 rate-book items and six contractors, without boiling the ocean.</li>
    <li>Translate the diagnosis into enforceable contract reforms ready for the 2026 RFP.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>My Role</h2>
  <p>I led the independent assessment end to end — designing the three-layer method, analysing 12 months of approved spend ($233M across 565,505 transactions, 482 rate-book items, six contractors), quantifying above-market exposure and isolating its structural root cause, and building the five-pillar contracting framework and phased roadmap.</p>

  <h2>The Approach</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Scope to what matters</strong> — Pareto-analysed the rate book: 45 of 482 items drove ~80% of the $233M.</li>
    <li><strong>URB gap assessment</strong> — applied a four-condition clean test, sorting items into governance buckets.</li>
    <li><strong>Variance deep dive</strong> — measured price spread and utilisation of the highest-priced contractor.</li>
    <li><strong>Commercial impact</strong> — quantified above-market billing per contractor per item, yielding the $4.9M–$6M opportunity.</li>
    <li><strong>Contracting reform</strong> — converted the diagnosis into a five-pillar framework and a phased roadmap.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Key Findings</h2>
  <div class="cs-cards">
    <div><p class="m">45 items</p><h4>Concentrated, therefore solvable</h4><p>45 of 482 rate-book items drove ~80% of the $233M — the governance issue is highly concentrated and operationally addressable.</p></div>
    <div><p class="m">Structural</p><h4>Root cause: structural, not supplier-specific</h4><p>The two largest contractors carried ~55% of variance, but the cause was the absence of rate enforcement — replacements would reproduce it.</p></div>
    <div><p class="m">$22.4M</p><h4>Ungoverned spend pocket</h4><p>Cost-plus spend sat outside any usage framework, letting unit rates act as effective floors and absorbing all crew-time overruns.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>Results</h2>
  <ul class="result-list">
    <li><strong>$4.9M–$6M exposure quantified</strong> and made entirely addressable; five-year value of fixing governance indicatively $20M–$28M.</li>
    <li><strong>A single structural lever</strong> identified — rate-book enforcement — avoiding a costly, ineffective contractor reshuffle.</li>
    <li><strong>An RFP-ready toolkit:</strong> a five-pillar contract framework, upgraded description standard, CMM usage guidance, and a standardized RFP pricing template.</li>
    <li><strong>A sequenced roadmap</strong> tied to the 2026 RFP critical path, with each reform mapped to a specific governance failure.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="cs-closing">
    <p>Rate renegotiation alone will not hold — without structural contract reform, contractors revert to misusing ambiguous rate descriptions in the next cycle. The five-pillar framework converts an indicative opportunity into a permanently governed programme, making rate improvements auditable and durable through the 2026 renewal and beyond.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="cs-note"><strong>Illustrative & anonymized.</strong> Client and contractor identities withheld; analysis is directional and demonstrates the method rather than reports exact figures.</p>
</CaseStudyLayout>
